The grid has 81 squares. Each tile covers 3 squares, so 26 tiles cover 78 squares, leaving 3 uncovered.

**Key observation:** The tiling uses only 1×3 tiles (horizontal or vertical). The number of uncovered squares must be compatible with the tiling.

A 1×3 tile covers 3 squares of the same color in a checkerboard coloring. A 9×9 grid has 41 squares of one color and 40 of the other. Each tile covers 2 squares of the majority color and 1 of the minority, or vice versa.

Let h = number of horizontal tiles, v = number of vertical tiles. Each horizontal tile covers 3 squares in a row (2 of one color, 1 of the other), each vertical tile covers 3 squares in a column (2 of one color, 1 of the other).

Total covered: 78 squares. Uncovered: 3 squares.

Let the majority color have 41 squares. Each tile covers 2 majority + 1 minority OR 1 majority + 2 minority.

Case 1: All tiles are horizontal. Each horizontal tile covers 2 black (say) + 1 white. Total covered: 26×2 = 52 black, 26 white. Uncovered: 41-52 = -11 black, 40-26 = 14 white. Impossible.

Case 2: All tiles vertical. Each vertical tile covers 2 black + 1 white. Total: 52 black, 26 white. Uncovered: -11 black, 14 white. Impossible.

Case 3: Mixed. Let h horizontal, v vertical, h + v = 26.

Black covered: 2h + v
White covered: h + 2v

Uncovered black: 41 - (2h + v)
Uncovered white: 40 - (h + 2v)

Both must be ≥ 0, and equal (since 3 uncovered total, they must be (3,0), (2,1), (1,2), (0,3)).

