This is false. The p-value is a measure of evidence against the null hypothesis, computed from the test statistic. The value 0.05 is a common significance level (α), not the typical p-value. P-values vary depending on the data and test statistic.

**Statement 2:** ""An alternative or research hypothesis is an assertion that holds if the null hypothesis is false.""

This is true by definition. The alternative hypothesis (H₁) is the hypothesis that contradicts the null hypothesis. It asserts that there is an effect or difference, which would be true if the null hypothesis is false.

**Statement 3:** ""A two-tail test is a test in which a null hypothesis can be rejected by an extreme result occurring in only one direction.""

This is false. In a two-tail test, the null hypothesis can be rejected by extreme results occurring in either direction (both tails). The statement describes a one-tail test.

**Statement 4:** ""The probability of a Type I error is represented by β, and is the probability of failing to reject a false null hypothesis.""

This is false. The probability of a Type I error (rejecting a true null hypothesis) is represented by α, not β. β represents the probability of a Type II error (failing to reject a false null hypothesis).

