**Definition recap:** \(a\) is bao-good if there exist integers \((s, l)\) such that:
1. There is no positive integer \(b\) with \(a \mid s^b - l\) (i.e., the order of \(s\) modulo \(a\) doesn't divide... wait, actually this means \(s^b \equiv l \pmod{a}\) has no solution for any positive integer \(b\), which is impossible unless \(a = 1\). 

Actually, condition 1 states: there does NOT exist a positive integer \(b\) with \(a \mid s^b - l\). This means \(s^b \not\equiv l \pmod{a}\) for all positive integers \(b\).

Condition 2: for every proper divisor \(a'\) of \(a\) (with \(1 \le a' < a\)), there EXISTS a positive integer \(b\) with \(a' \mid s^b - l\).

**Key observation:** If \(a = 1\), condition 2 is vacuously true (no proper divisors), and condition 1: there is no positive integer \(b\) with \(1 \mid s^b - l\), which is false since \(1 \mid\) everything. So \(a = 1\) is not bao-good.

For \(a > 1\), condition 1 requires \(s^b \not\equiv l \pmod{a}\) for all \(b \ge 1\). This means \(l\) is not in the image of the map \(b \mapsto s^b \bmod a\).

Condition 2 requires that for each proper divisor \(a'\), the congruence \(s^b \equiv l \pmod{a'}\) has a solution.

**Using the Chinese Remainder Theorem:** If \(a = a_1 a_2 \cdots a_k\) with pairwise coprime \(a_i\), then \(s^b \equiv l \pmod{a}\) has a solution iff \(s^b \equiv l \pmod{a_i}\) has a solution for all \(i\).

