Let $z = e^{i\theta}$, so $\theta$ goes from $0$ to $\pi$ corresponding to $z$ moving along the upper half of the unit circle from $1$ to $-1$.

$\tan(\theta + ia) = \frac{\sin(\theta+ia)}{\cos(\theta+ia)}$

Using $\sin(\theta+ia) = \frac{e^{i(\theta+ia) - e^{-i(\theta+ia)}{2i}$ and $\cos(\theta+ia) = \frac{e^{i(\theta+ia) + e^{-i(\theta+ia)}{2}$:

$$\tan(\theta+ia) = \frac{e^{i\theta - a} - e^{-i\theta - a}}{i(e^{i\theta - a} + e^{-i\theta - a})}$$

As $\theta$ goes from $0$ to $\pi$, $e^{i\theta}$ goes from $1$ to $-1$ along the upper half-circle.

The integral becomes:
$$I = \int_{\text{upper half}} \frac{e^{i\theta - a} - e^{-i\theta - a}}{i(e^{i\theta - a} + e^{-i\theta - a})}\, i\frac{dz}{iz}$$

Since $dz = ie^{i\theta}\, d\theta$, so $d\theta = \frac{dz}{iz}$.

$$I = \int_{|z|=1, \Im(z)\geq 0} \frac{z^{-a} - z^{-1-a}}{z^{-a} + z^{-1-a}} \cdot \frac{dz}{z}$$

$$I = \int_{|z|=1, \Im(z)\geq 0} \frac{z - 1}{z + 1} \cdot \frac{dz}{z}$$

The integrand is $\frac{z-1}{z(z+1)}$.

Poles at $z=0$ and $z=-1$.

Along the upper half-circle, the pole at $z=-1$ is on the boundary. Since the pole is of order 1, the contribution from the pole at $z=-1$ is $\frac{1}{2}\cdot 2\pi i \cdot \text{Res}_{z=-1}$... Actually, for a simple pole on the boundary, the integral equals $\pi i$ times the residue if the pole is of odd order... 

The pole at $z=-1$ is simple. The residue is $\lim_{z\to -1} (z+1)\frac{z-1}{z(z+1)} = \frac{-2}{-1} = 2$.

By the pole-on-boundary rule (or using the formula $\int_{|z|=1} f(z)\, dz = \pi i \cdot \text{Res}_{z=-1}$... actually the full integral over the full circle would be $2\pi i \cdot (2) = 4\pi i$, but we only want the upper half).

Actually: $\int_{\text{upper half}} \frac{z-1}{z(z+1)}\, dz = \pi i \cdot \text{Res}_{z=-1} + \text{contribution from } z=0$

Residue at $z=0$: $\frac{0-1}{0+1} = -1$

